Installation Guide for PHP Job Seeker 2
========================================

Prerequisites
-------------

- Apache httpd (or similar web server) with PHP module
- PHP 8.0 or later (tested with PHP 8.4)
- MySQL 8.0 or later (tested with MySQL 8.4)
- PHP mysqli extension
- HTTPS recommended (required for secure session cookies)

In your PHP configuration (/etc/php.ini on Unix), set the timezone. For example,
if you're in the Central US timezone:

    date.timezone = America/Chicago

Installation Steps
------------------

1) Clone the repository into your web server's document root:

    git clone git@github.com:kbcmdba/pjs2.git /var/www/html/pjs2

2) Create the MySQL database and application user:

    mysql -e "CREATE DATABASE pjs2;"
    mysql -e "CREATE USER 'pjs2_app'@'127.0.0.1' IDENTIFIED BY 'YourPasswordHere';"
    mysql -e "GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON pjs2.* TO 'pjs2_app'@'127.0.0.1';"
    mysql -e "FLUSH PRIVILEGES;"

3) Copy config_sample.xml to config.xml and update it with your settings:

    cp config_sample.xml config.xml

   Required settings in config.xml:
   - dbHost, dbPort, dbName, dbUser, dbPass: your MySQL connection details
   - timeZone: your local timezone (e.g., America/Chicago)
   - userId, userPassword: fallback credentials for the web interface
     (used when there are no users in the user table yet)

   Security settings:
   - resetOk: set to 0 in production (1 allows database reset via resetDb.php)
   - skipAuth: set to 0 in production (1 disables authentication entirely)

4) Initialize the database by visiting resetDb.php in your browser or running:

    php-cgi resetDb.php

   This creates all tables, triggers, and seed data.

   WARNING: resetDb.php drops and recreates all tables. Only run this on
   initial setup or when you want to start fresh. It requires admin role
   access and resetOk=1 in config.xml.

5) Log in using the userId/userPassword from config.xml. Once logged in,
   create user accounts via the user table in MySQL:

    mysql pjs2 -e "INSERT INTO user (userName, userPassword, role, created, updated)
                   VALUES ('yourname', SHA2('YourPassword', 256), 'admin', NOW(), NOW());"

   Available roles: admin, user

   After creating a user account, log in with those credentials instead.
   Admin users can access resetDb.php and manage application statuses.
   Regular users can manage jobs, companies, contacts, searches, and keywords.

MySQL 8 Notes
-------------

MySQL 8 introduced two changes that affect installation:

a) GRANT ALL ON dbname.* no longer implicitly allows creating the database.
   You must create the database (step 2 above) before the application user
   can use it.

b) If binary logging is enabled, you must allow the application user to
   create triggers:

    mysql -e "SET GLOBAL log_bin_trust_function_creators = 1;"

   To make this persistent across MySQL restarts, add to your MySQL
   configuration (e.g., /etc/my.cnf or /etc/my.cnf.d/*.cnf):

    [mysqld]
    log_bin_trust_function_creators = 1

   Run this before step 4 (resetDb.php), or trigger creation will fail.

Apache SSL Configuration (Recommended)
---------------------------------------

PJS2 uses secure session cookies (HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict).
For these to work properly, serve the site over HTTPS.

For production or internet-facing servers, Let's Encrypt provides free,
automatically-renewing SSL certificates:

    dnf install certbot python3-certbot-apache   # Fedora/RHEL
    apt install certbot python3-certbot-apache    # Debian/Ubuntu

    certbot --apache -d your-hostname

Certbot will configure Apache automatically and set up auto-renewal.
See https://letsencrypt.org for more details.

For local development, you can generate a self-signed certificate instead:

    openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
        -keyout /etc/pki/tls/private/localhost.key \
        -out /etc/pki/tls/certs/localhost.crt

Example Apache SSL virtual host snippet (if configuring manually):

    <VirtualHost *:443>
        ServerName your-hostname
        DocumentRoot /var/www/html
        SSLEngine on
        SSLCertificateFile /etc/pki/tls/certs/your-cert.pem
        SSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/pki/tls/private/your-key.pem
    </VirtualHost>

Development Setup
-----------------

If you want a separate development checkout from the web-served copy:

    git clone git@github.com:kbcmdba/pjs2.git ~/work/pjs2

Make changes in the development checkout, commit, push, then pull in the
web checkout to deploy:

    cd /var/www/html/pjs2
    git pull
